tened the core of Christian belief. Gilman also trains his critical eye on the works of Jonson, Donne, Pepys, and Defoe, which, he posits, can be more fully understood when put into the context of this century-long project to “write out” the plague. Ultimately, Plague Writing in Early Modern England is more than a compendium of artifacts of a bygone era; it holds up a distant mirror to reflect our own condition in the age of AIDS, super viruses, multidrug resistant tuberculosis, and the hovering threat of a global flu pandemic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDiseases and literaturexHistoryx17th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aDiseases and literaturezGreat BritainxHistoryy17th century. 0aDiseases in literature. 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticismxEarly modern, 1500-1700. 0aEnglish literatureyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aEpidemics in literature. 0aEpidemicsxHistoryx17th centuryxEngland. 0aEpidemicszEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aLiterature and societyxHistoryx17th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aLiterature and societyzGreat BritainxHistoryy17th century. 0aPlague in literature. 0aPlaguexHistoryx17th centuryxEngland. 0aPlaguexPolitical aspects. 0aPlaguexReligious aspects. 0aPlaguezEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226294117423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226294117.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles